About
Between the Appia Nuova and Tuscolana streets, the mighty structures of the Roman aqueducts Aqua Marcia, Claudia and Anio Novus stand out in the countryside. The Aqua Marcia, built between 144 and 140 BC. by the praetor Quinto Marcio Re, it is the longest aqueduct in Rome. Between the second and first centuries. B.C. the conduits of two other aqueducts were superimposed on it: the Aqua Tepula and the Aqua Iulia. Aqua Claudia was started by Caligula in 38 AD. and finished by Claudius in 52 AD. Anio Novus was also commissioned by Caligula and finished by Claudius in 52 AD. The emperor, having already given his name to the other aqueduct, dedicated this water to the Aniene river using the adjective "novus" to distinguish it from the "vetus", already existing since 272 BC. The Anio Novus shared a large part of its route with the Aqua Claudia whose structures it overlapped. The best preserved stretch is clearly visible above the Aqua Claudia, inside the Parco degli Acquedotti.
Duration: 1-2 hours

Ancient remains, off the beaten track
May 2022
Rome is known as the water city; as the heart of the then empire, engineers had to work out how to transport more water possible to satisfy the city's population needs. Is possible to see in this park six of the eleven aqueducts that transported fresh water to Rome.

Not all aqueducts are of Roman origin, there is one of Medieval origin and some of them are juxtaposed one to other.

This is a popular park where locals like to hang out, picnic or simply for sport purposes. We rented some bikes in the area and we biked throughout this park, Tor Fiscale (nothing of great interest) and the Appian Way which is somehow tricky to get there but not impossible.

P.S. closet metro stations are Lucio Sestio or Lucio Agricola

dapper777
Monaco66,929 contributions
Highly recommended.
Jan 2023 • Friends
The Parco degli Acquedotti is an urban green area of Rome.
It is included between the Appio Claudio district, via delle Capannelle and the Rome-Cassino-Naples railway line, covering an area of approximately 240 hectares.
The name derives from the presence on the surface or underground of seven Roman and papal aqueducts which supplied the ancient Rome.
When we visited the site, we admired and enjoyed seductive landscapes of wild and still untouched nature.
Certainly it is one of the most fascinating parks in Rome.
It is enclosed between Via Appia and Via Tuscolana, between the scenic attractions of the Roman countryside up to the area of the Castelli Romani, in an atmosphere as it has been frozen in time, extremely enjoyable in the pink light of the sunset, when the imposing arches of the Claudio and Felice aqueducts, framed by pine trees, stand out against the sun in all their suggestive and evocative beauty.
Rich in history, the Parco degli Acquedotti is one of the green lungs of the city and is part of the Suburban Regional Park of the Appia Antica.
Its name derives from the fact that here was the hub of the water network of ancient Rome, where the aqueducts that supplied the capital with water, the immense patrician villas, the baths and the fountains intersected, joined and overlapped.
Highly recommended.

Scott
San Francisco, CA6,660 contributions
Amazing
Jan 2022 • Solo
Having visited Rome a few times, it was absolutely fantastic to find a amazing the aqueduct park. There are literally zero tourists. I don't mind tourists, but this place is 100% locals. There's a dog park. There are tennis courts. And there are countless locals jogging and walking throughout the park.

But most importantly, there are aqueducts.

This is probably the most interesting Park featuring ancient critical infrastructure on the planet. Read up a little bit on these aqueducts and you will enjoy the park even more. There are some interpretive signs, but there are not signs easily identifying the various aqueduct. But if you go to Google maps you will find pens marking them with names.

Also shop around on YouTube for some interesting videos about the aqueducts. This is a place where several aqueducts came together just before entering the city of rome. A unique opportunity to see just about every type of aqueduct. Here you'll also see the oldest paved road in the Roman empire I know you thought the Appian Way was that road but it's not full stop do a little research and you'll appreciate the road even more.

Pittsburgh, PA42 contributions
Safe for a solo traveler in the evening
Jun 2021 • Solo
I was here to paint a watercolor or two. I wanted to get off the beaten path away from the city to see trees again. I saw the site on an itinerary from an e-bike tour that was reviewed on Trip Advisor. It is a short walk from the metro - maybe 3-4 blocks, headed toward the church. There were cafes and a grocery store on the way. Across from the metro is a Lilly cafe (the opposite direction of where you want to go) from the Guilio Agricola metro station. As others mentioned it is a free park and for this Sunday evening, a lot of people were outside playing or having picnics. A combination of families, bikers, kids, and couples. It was an impressive site with a lot of trails. Some of the ruins were covered in graffiti toward the bottom. A view included a mountain with roman trees in the forefront and haystacks near where I painted. It was beautiful. I would have liked to be there longer but it was getting dark and less people were at the park then. I felt safe the whole time. My only fear was my paintbrushes blowing away. I would have loved to have been able to be there longer than my time allowed to explore more of it. I loved being amongst the roman trees and other trees and farming like landscape with the haystacks and wild flowers, a dreamscape of color!

Off the beaten track
Jul 2021 • Couples
What an amazing find. A 5-minutes walk from any one of a handful of metro stations on line A. The park is rather unkempt (natural) with with gravel and dirt walking trails, but what an insight into the marvellous engineering ingenuity of the ancient Romans. These were and still are massive structures. Factoid. The average American users 150 gallons of water per day. These aqueducts supplied Roman citizens with the equivalent of 200 gallons per day, and could also be used to supply lower grade water (as well as drinking water) to wash out drains away from the city.

Margaret M
72 contributions
We took the metro Red Line (Line A) to the Giulio Agricola stop (it's pretty far out from the center of town, but you just keep riding). From there, you'll need a map to help you figure out which way to walk, but you just come up out of the Metro and walk down (or up) the main road you're on for a few blocks and you hit the park. No turns necessary.
